        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to measure the 345 GHz continuum flux and the CO v=0 2-1 line flux from the newly spatially resolved edge-on debris disk around HD 30447.

We conservatively model the spatial distribution of the dust, assuming (1) the millimeter-sized grains are co-spatial radially with the micron-sized dust grains as detected in the NICMOS image and (2) the scale height of the disk is determined by dynamical models including planets with masses, MEarth – 0.3 MJup. We use MCFOST to generate model images of an edge-on disk with a total flux scaled to the APEX LABOCA measurements. In MCFOST, we specify the scale height of a disk as a power law, H = Ho(R/Ro)^?, with Ro = Rinner, Ho = Hinner, and ? = 1.95; this specification reproduces the scale height as a function of radius to first order. We used the CASA 'simalma' task to simulate ALMA observations assuming the C34-3 antenna configuration, 0.913 PWV (3rd octile) and 3.1 hours of on-source integration time, corresponding to 7.3 hours of observatory time including overheads. We used the CASA 'clean' task with 1000 iteration to reconstruct the image (see Figure 3). We did not use a sophisticated image model that assumed any morphology.
We used a clean box region around the area of known emission in both cases. We think the size of the box can be reasonably guessed from the dirty map morphology. The cleaning threshold was set to 80nJy. All other parameters were left as the defaults. With this partial clean we demonstrate a strong detection of the disk structure and relative brightness, both of which can be used to place limits on the scale height compared with MCFOST dust modeling.Based on submillimeter observations of birth rings in other debris disks, we expect that the dust will probably be more narrowly confined than we have assumed.

We estimate the CO line flux generated by collisions between planetesimals assuming (1) the disks are experiencing a collisional cascade, (2) the disks produce 50 times more CO (relative to dust) than comets in our solar system like 49 Cet; (3) the photo dissociation lifetime of the gas is ~500 years; gas around F-type stars is expected to photo-dissociate more slowly; and (4) the gas is in collisional equilibrium with the dust and possesses an excitation temperature, Tex ~ 100 K. We calculate the flux density of the CO v=0 2-1 line fluxes for our target, assuming that the disk possesses a maximum rotational velocity ~4 km s-1.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
