    <prp:abstract>We have recently imaged a new edge-on debris disk in scattered light by reprocessing the coronagraphic HST NICMOS archive using a principal component analysis (Soummer et al. 2014). We propose to obtain ALMA Band 7 observations, in Spectral Line mode at center frequencies of 345.8, 344.0, 334.0, and 332.2 GHz for HD 30447, of our newly resolved target, to (1) measure the scale height of the disk and determine whether the disk hosts a planet with a mass &gt; MNeptume, (2) measure the location of the parent body belt(s), and (3) constrain the mass of CO in the disk that may be generated by collisions between comet-like parent bodies. The submillimeter thermal emission from the HD 30447 disk has already been detected using APEX LABOCA at 870 μm with &gt;2.5σ confidence (Nilsson et al. 2010). Constraining the presence of the most massive bodies (planets and parent bodies) is critical to understanding the evolutionary status of any debris disk because the formation and migration of planets drives debris disk evolution.</prp:abstract>
